An Algorithm is a recipe to solve a problem¶

  • There may be many algorithms for solving a particular problem.

    • Can you name one problem where we saw this?

  • Since there are different solutions, not all of them are equally efficient.

    • How do we compare them?
  • ifact(20) : 1.38 µs ± 3.57 ns
  • rfact(20) : 3.91 µs ± 8.07 ns
  • ifact(200) : 18.2 µs ± 295 ns
  • rfact(200) : 47.8 µs ± 357 ns
ifact( ) ~3 times faster than rfact( )¶
  • iexp(20) : 1.01 µs ± 5.36 ns
  • rexp(20) : 1.28 µs ± 10.2 ns
  • iexp(200): 10.9 µs ± 44.5 ns
  • rexp(200): 2.25 µs ± 8.17 ns
Which one is faster?¶

How to compare different programs?¶

  • Measure their execution times
    • Depends upon data
    • Depends upon the hardware (clock speed, branch prediction and pipelining)
    • Depends upon whether it is a multi-user system or a single-user system
      • context-switching and interrupt handling
      • Memory access and cache performance
    • Depends upon the programming language
      • compiler, optimiser, interpreter...
    • Depends on the time of the day :-)

So, what do we do?¶

We need an implementation independent way of doing this...

  • Can we examine the solution and measure those aspects of the algorithm that most critically affect its execution time?

  • For example, we could count the number of logical comparisons, data interchanges, or arithmetic operations.

Count the number of additions (matadd-v1)¶

n = 10

totalSum = 0

for i in range( n ) :

rowSum[i] = 0    
for j in range( n ) :
    rowSum[i] = rowSum[i] + matrix[i,j]
    totalSum = totalSum + matrix[i,j]

  • Inner loop has 2 additions, which goes n times: 2n

  • Outer loop has n iterations.

  • So, total number of additions: $2n \times n = 2n^2$

Can we reduce the number of additions?

Count the number of additions (matadd-v2)¶

n = 10

totalSum = 0

for i in range( n ) :

rowSum[i] = 0    
for j in range( n ) :
    rowSum[i] = rowSum[i] + matrix[i,j]
totalSum = totalSum + rowSum[i]  <-- Add rowSum after inner loop is over

  • inner loop has 1 addtion, which goes n times: n

  • outer loop has n iterations: $n^2$

  • outer loop has 1 addition: n

  • So, total number of additions: $n^2 + n < 2n^2$

Compare matadd-v1 and matadd-v2¶

  • matadd-v1 needs $2n^2$ additions

  • matadd-v2 needs $n^2 + n$ additions

What would we like to measure?¶

  • We shall be interested in in the rate of growth of the time or space required to solve larger and larger instances of a problem.

  • We would like to associate with a problem an integer, called the size of the problem, which is a measure of the quantity of input data.

  • The time needed by an algorithm expressed as a function of the size of a problem is called the time complexity of the algorithm.

  • The space needed by an algorithm expressed as a function of the size of a problem is called the space complexity of the algorithm.

What would we like to measure? ...¶

  • Instead of counting the precise number of operations or steps, computer scientists are more interested in classifying an algorithm based on the order of magnitude as applied to execution time or space requirements.

  • This classification approximates the actual number of required steps for execution or the actual storage requirements in terms of variable-sized data sets.

  • The term big-Oh, which is derived from the expression “on the order of,” is used to specify an algorithm’s classification.

What is Big-Oh?¶

  • Assume we have a function $T(n)$ that represents the approximate number of steps required by an algorithm for an input of size $n$.

  • For matadd-v2, we can write: $$T(n) = n^2 + n $$

  • Now, suppose there exists a function $f(n)$ for $n\geq 0$, such that for some constant $c$, and some constant $m$, $$T(n) \leq c f(n),$$ for all values of $n \geq m$.

https://www.desmos.com/calculator/qgvssvewsn

  • Suppose $f(n) = n^3$ and $T(n) = n^2 + n$.

    • $f(1) = 1,\;\; T(1) = 2$
    • $f(2) = 8,\;\; T(2) = 6$
    • $f(3) = 27,\; T(3) = 12$

  • $T(n) \leq cf(n)$, for $c = 1$ and $m = 2 (n\geq m)$.

  • $T(n) \leq cf(n)$, for $c = 3$ and $m = 1 (n\geq m)$.

What is Big-Oh?¶

  • Such an algorithm $T(n)$ is said to have a time-complexity of, or executes on the order of, $f(n)$ relative to the number of operations it requires.

  • There exists a positive integer $m$ and a constant $c$ (constant of proportionality) such that for all $n\geq m$, $T(n) \leq cf(n)$.

  • We say $T(n)$ runs on the order of $f(n)$: $$ T(n) = O(f(n)) = O(n^3)$$

  • The function $f(n)$ provides an upper bound for the running time of $T(n)$.

  • The objective usually is to find a function $f(\cdot)$ that is the lowest upper bound.

Big-Oh Notation¶

  • The objective usually is to find a function $f(\cdot)$ that is the lowest upper bound.

  • Can we find a tighter upper bound for $T(n) = n^2 + n$

    • $f(n) = n^3$

    • $f(n) = 1000 n^2$

    • $f(n) = 3 n^2$

    • $f(n) = 2 n^2$

Find the $c$ and $m$ for the above upper bounds¶

Growth Rate of Some Common Functions

An example¶

  • Suppose $T(n) = n^2 + log_2 n + 3n$
    • Which is the dominating (largest) term when...
      • n = 1?
      • n = 2?
      • n = 3?
      • n = 4?

An example...¶

  • $T(n) = n^2 + log_2 n + 3n$

  1. $n^2 + log_2 n + 3n \leq n^2 + n^2 + n^2 $

  2. $n^2 + log_2 n + 3n \leq 3n^2$

  • $T(n) = O(n^2)$
    • $\because T(n)\leq 3n^2, c = 3, f(n) = n^2 $

  • $T(n) = 2n^2 + 15n + 500$

  • Find $f(n), c, m$ such that $T(n) = O(f(n))$.

Constant of Proportionality¶

  • The constant of proportionality is only crucial when two algorithms have the same $f(n)$.

  • It usually makes no difference when comparing algorithms whose growth rates are of different magnitudes.

    • Suppose we have two algorithms, $L_1$ and $L_2$, with run times equal to $n^2$ and $2n$ respectively.
    • $L_1$ has a time-complexity of $O(n^2)$ with $c=1$ and $L_2$ has a time complexity of $O(n)$ with $c=2$.
    • Even though $L_1$ has a smaller constant of proportionality, $L_1$ is still slower and, in fact an order of magnitude slower, for large values of $n$.

Constructing T(n)¶

  • Instead of counting the number of logical comparisons or arithmetic operations, we evaluate an algorithm by considering every operation.

  • For simplicity, we assume that each basic operation or statement, at the abstract level, takes the same amount of time and, thus, each is assumed to cost constant time.

  • For all practical purposes, we can ignore the first line of the algorithm.

Pseudocode¶

  • An algorithm expressed with all the necessary details
  • Independent of the syntax of any particular programming language

  • The limiting behaviour of the compiexity as size increases is called the asymptotic time complexity.

  • Analogous definitions can be made for space complexity and asymptotic space complexity.

Various running times¶

  • Some algorithms' times differ even for inputs of the same size

    • Suppose arr = [1,4,3,2]
      • insatind(arr,3,6) should return [1,4,6,3,2]

$\longrightarrow$

  • Write a function srch(array,element) that searches the array for the element and returns the index (position) in the array if the element is found, and -1 otherwise.¶
    • Suppose arr = [1,4,3,2]
      • srch(arr,3) should return 3
      • srch(arr,6) should return -1

Various running times...¶

  • Some algorithms' times differ even for inputs of the same size

    • In searching in an unsorted array, an element at the beginning is found faster.
    • Adding an element at the beginning of an array is slower than at the end.

  • Such algorithms can be evaluated for their best, worst, and average cases (and therefore, times).

srch(array,element)¶

  • best case: when element is first in the array

  • worst case: when element is not in the array

  • average case?

  • Generally, we are interested in the worst case time-complexity.

Finding the time-complexity of a recursive algorithm¶

def fact1(n):
    if n == 1:
        return 1
    if n == 0:
        return 1
    return(n*fact1(n-1))

Recurrence Equation (or Recurrence Relation)¶

def fact1(n):
    if n == 1:
        return 1
    if n == 0:
        return 1
    return(n*fact1(n-1))

$$ T(n) = \left\{ \begin{array}\\ 1 & \mbox{if } \ n = 1 \\ 1+T(n-1) & \mbox{if } \ n > 1 \\ \end{array} \right.$$

$$ T(n) = \left\{ \begin{array}\\ 1 & \mbox{if } \ n = 1 \\ 1+T(n-1) & \mbox{if } \ n > 1 \\ \end{array} \right.$$

$T(n) = 1 + (1 + T(n - 2))$

$T(n) = 2 + T(n - 2)$

$T(n) = 2 + (1 + T(n - 3))$

$T(n) = 3 + T(n - 3)$

$$ T(n) = \left\{ \begin{array}\\ 1 & \mbox{if } \ n = 1 \\ 1+T(n-1) & \mbox{if } \ n > 1 \\ \end{array} \right.$$

$T(n) = 1 + (1 + T(n - 2))$

$T(n) = 2 + T(n - 2)$

$T(n) = 2 + (1 + T(n - 3))$

$T(n) = 3 + T(n - 3)$

$T(n) = n-1 + T(n - (n-1))$

$T(n) = n-1 + T(1)$

$T(n) = n-1 + 1$

$T(n) = O(n)$

Recurrence Equation (or Recurrence Relation)¶

def fact1(n):
    assert n >= 0 and int(n) == n, "positive integers only, please! :-) "
    if n == 1:
        return 1
    if n == 0:
        return 1
    return(n*fact1(n-1))

$$ T(n) = \left\{ \begin{array}\\ c & \mbox{if } \ n = 1 \\ c+T(n-1) & \mbox{if } \ n > 1 \\ \end{array} \right.$$

$$ T(n) = \left\{ \begin{array}\\ c & \mbox{if } \ n = 1 \\ c+T(n-1) & \mbox{if } \ n > 1 \\ \end{array} \right.$$

$T(n) = c + (c + T(n - 2))$

$T(n) = 2c + T(n - 2)$

$T(n) = 2c + (c + T(n - 3)$

$$ T(n) = \left\{ \begin{array}\\ c & \mbox{if } \ n = 1 \\ c+T(n-1) & \mbox{if } \ n > 1 \\ \end{array} \right.$$

$T(n) = c + (c + T(n - 2))$

$T(n) = 2c + T(n - 2)$

$T(n) = 2c + (c + T(n - 3)$

$T(n) = 3c + T(n - 3)$

$T(n) = nc + T(n - n)$

$T(n) = nc + T(0)$

$T(n) = nc + c$

$T(n) = O(n)$

$$ T(n) = \left\{ \begin{array}\\ c & \mbox{if } \ n = 1 \\ c+T(n/2) & \mbox{if } \ n > 1 \\ \end{array} \right.$$

$$ T(n) = \left\{ \begin{array}\\ c & \mbox{if } \ n = 1 \\ c+T(n/2) & \mbox{if } \ n > 1 \\ \end{array} \right.$$

$T(n) = c + T(n/2)) \implies T(n) = c + [c + T(n/4)] \implies T(n) = 2c + T(n/4)$

$T(n) = 2c + [c + T(n/8)] \implies T(n) = 3c + T(n/8)$

$T(n) = 3c + T(n/2^3)$

$T(n) = 3c + [c + T(n/2^4)] \implies T(n) = 4c + T(n/2^4)$

$$ T(n) = \left\{ \begin{array}\\ c & \mbox{if } \ n = 1 \\ c+T(n/2) & \mbox{if } \ n > 1 \\ \end{array} \right.$$

$T(n) = c + T(n/2)) \implies T(n) = c + [c + T(n/4)] \implies T(n) = 2c + T(n/4)$

$T(n) = 2c + [c + T(n/8)] \implies T(n) = 3c + T(n/8)$

$T(n) = 3c + T(n/2^3)$

When will we reach T(1) ?¶
Suppose $2^k = n,$¶

$T(n) = kc + T(n/2^k)$

$T(n) = (k+1)c$

That is $k = \log_2(n)$¶

$T(n) = O(\log n)$
